The above is an example of how to use placeholders in a JSON format. It's important to note that the placeholders are not actual values, but rather indicate where the real value will go when the document is filled out. In this case, the placeholder for the crew member name is denoted as [Crew member name]. This means that when the document is filled out, the actual crew member name will replace the placeholder. The same goes for other placeholders in the document.

It's also worth noting that the placeholders can be used in any part of the document, including within arrays or objects. For instance, if there were multiple crew members on the Beta cruiser, their names could be listed in an array like so:

"crew": [
    {"name": "[Crew member name 1]},
    {"name": "[Crew member name 2]}"
],

This would allow for two different crew member names to be added to the document.

In summary, placeholders provide a way to leave blank spaces in a document that will later be filled with specific information. They make it easier to create templates and forms that can be customized to fit specific needs.
